metadata.title: Bell OH-58 Kiowa
aws::graph::propositions: Bell OH-58 Kiowa Deployment and Naming in Australia and Other Countries
OH-58As were partially disassembled and shipped to Australia.
The first OH-58As in Australia were given the name Kalkadoon rather than Kiowa.
Army minister Bob Katter Sr. suggested the name Kalkadoon for OH-58As in Australia.
Bob Katter Sr. wished to honor the Kalkadoon people of Queensland rather than a Native American people.
The Kalkadoon are people of Queensland.
The Kiowa are a Native American people.
The new OH-58A helicopters in Australia were affixed with boomerang-shaped decals bearing the name Kalkadoon.
The renaming of OH-58As to Kalkadoon was poorly received by the Australian Army.
The name Kalkadoon for OH-58As was dropped after Bob Katter Sr.'s term as minister concluded.
OH-58A helicopters had reportedly been nicknamed "Kattercopters" by Australian Army personnel.
OH-58A helicopters in the Australian naval fleet were retired in 2000.
A total of 74 OH-58As were delivered to the Canadian Armed Forces as COH-58A.
The COH-58A helicopters were later redesignated CH-136 Kiowa in Canada.
As many as 12 surplus OH-58A Kiowas were sold to the Dominican Republic Air Force.
Some surplus OH-58A Kiowas were sold privately in Australia.

text:
then partially disassembled and shipped to Australia, where they were reassembled.
The first OH-58As in Australia were given the name Kalkadoon rather than Kiowa, at the suggestion of army minister Bob Katter Sr. who wished to honor the Kalkadoon people of Queensland rather than a Native American people. The new helicopters were affixed with "boomerang-shaped decals bearing the name Kalkadoon". The renaming was apparently poorly received by the Army and was dropped after Katter's term as minister concluded; the helicopters had reportedly been nicknamed "Kattercopters" by army personnel. Helicopters in the naval fleet were retired in 2000.
A total of 74 OH-58As were delivered to the Canadian Armed Forces as COH-58A and later redesignated CH-136 Kiowa. As many as 12 surplus Kiowas were sold to the Dominican Republic Air Force, and others sold privately in Australia.
